## Quick Verdict

**The Wallbox Pulsar Plus is a competent, stylish charger at a competitive price — but its customer support reputation is a genuine concern.** If you value a beautiful design and a simple app above all else, it delivers. But if you want smart tariff integration or responsive after-sales support, there are better options in the UK market right now.

**Pros:**
- Most compact home charger on the market
- Stylish design with LED lighting
- Genuinely intuitive, easy-to-use app
- Competitive pricing (from ~£550 installed)
- Built-in PEN protection saves on installation costs
- No earth rod required

**Cons:**
- No smart tariff integration (no Intelligent Octopus support)
- Customer support is inconsistent and slow
- Only a 2-year warranty (shorter than most competitors)
- Glossy plastic finish may not appeal to everyone
- No solar panel integration
- Barcelona-based support team — UK-specific issues can take longer to resolve

---

## Design and Build

This is where the Wallbox Pulsar Plus genuinely excels. At just 166mm × 163mm, it's the smallest home EV charger on the UK market. It looks sleek on a wall, and the LED lighting ring around the front gives it a premium, modern feel that most competitors can't match.

The build quality is good despite the plastic construction. The glossy finish divides opinion — some love it, others find it looks a bit cheap in certain lights — but in its price bracket, the Pulsar Plus is comfortably the best-looking option.

It's IP54 rated, which means it handles rain and dust without issue. Perfectly adequate for UK conditions, though slightly below the IP65 rating you'll find on the [Pod Point Solo 3](/reviews/pod-point-solo-3-review/).

One practical benefit: built-in open PEN fault protection means you don't need a separate earth rod installed. This saves £100–£150 on installation and keeps the final result neater — no metal spike in your garden.

## Charging Speed

The Pulsar Plus delivers 7.4kW on a single-phase supply — the standard maximum for UK home charging. That translates to roughly 25–30 miles of range per hour, which means a typical EV goes from near-empty to full in 6–10 hours overnight.

This is identical to the [Ohme Home Pro](/reviews/ohme-home-pro-review/) and marginally faster than the Pod Point Solo 3's 7.2kW. In practice, you won't notice the difference between any of these — they all deliver a full charge overnight without issue.

## The myWallbox App

The myWallbox app is genuinely one of the Pulsar Plus's strongest selling points. It's clean, colourful, and uses large buttons that make navigation intuitive. Setting up a charge schedule takes about 30 seconds — which sounds like it should be a given, but plenty of competing apps make this unnecessarily complicated.

Key app features:
- Charge scheduling (set days and times)
- Real-time charging status
- Energy usage history
- Power adjustment (you can limit charge rate)
- Multi-charger management

What the app doesn't do is integrate with smart electricity tariffs. There's no Intelligent Octopus support, no dynamic pricing, and no automatic optimisation based on energy costs. You set your charging window manually, and that's it.

For many people, this is perfectly adequate. Set your cheap-rate window once, forget about it. But compared to the Ohme Home Pro's fully automated approach, it feels a generation behind in terms of smart features.

## Smart Features — Or Lack Thereof

Let's be direct: the Wallbox Pulsar Plus is not a "smart" charger in the way that UK energy-conscious buyers increasingly expect. It has Wi-Fi and Bluetooth connectivity, a scheduling app, and basic usage tracking. That's it.

There's no:
- Smart tariff integration (Intelligent Octopus, Agile, etc.)
- Solar panel integration or energy diversion
- Dynamic load balancing with your household
- Carbon intensity tracking

If you're on a flat-rate electricity tariff and simply want to schedule overnight charging, the Pulsar Plus handles that perfectly well. But if you're on Octopus or a similar smart tariff and want your charger to automatically find the cheapest slots, you need an [Ohme Home Pro](/reviews/ohme-home-pro-review/) instead.

## The Customer Support Problem

This is the elephant in the room — and it's significant enough that at least one major UK installer (Smart Home Charge) stopped selling Wallbox products entirely because of it.

Wallbox's customer support is based in Barcelona, and UK customers have consistently reported slow response times, unresolved issues, and a general lack of urgency when things go wrong. Software bugs and firmware issues have been reported, and getting them fixed can involve weeks of back-and-forth.

To be fair: the majority of customers will never need to contact support. The hardware itself is reliable, and most people install it, set up the app, and never think about it again. But if something does go wrong, the support experience is a genuine weakness compared to UK-based competitors like Ohme, Pod Point, or myenergi.

This is a meaningful concern, and it's the main reason our rating is lower than the hardware alone would justify.

## Installation

Installation is straightforward and typically completes in 2–3 hours. The built-in PEN protection is a genuine advantage — it eliminates the need for an earth rod, saving both cost and hassle.

The Pulsar Plus is tethered-only (no untethered option), which suits most UK buyers. The cable is a standard length, though it's worth checking it reaches your usual parking position before committing.

The charger is OZEV grant eligible, so renters and flat owners can claim up to £350 towards installation costs. See our [OZEV grant guide](/guides/ev-charger-government-grant-uk/) for eligibility details.

## Value for Money

At ~£550–£650 installed (before the OZEV grant), the Wallbox Pulsar Plus is competitively priced. After the grant, you could be looking at as little as £200–£300 — which is genuinely excellent value for a charger with this build quality and app experience.

The question is whether the savings are worth the trade-offs: no smart tariff integration, weaker customer support, and a shorter warranty than most competitors.

